[Student "S"]
{You dealt this hand.  

You open with a Weak 2-Bid, 2\H. Partner responds 2NT. What do you say next? 

The 2NT bid is forcing and you have better than a minimum. You show your "feature" by bidding 3\C. Partner now bids the game.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "4"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "All"]
[Deal "W:96.KQT763.754.J7 T73.A8.J92.KT952 KJ54.J52.AQT3.A8 AQ82.94.K86.Q643"]
[Declarer "W"]
[Contract "3H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "W"]
2H pass 2NT pass 3H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 4, chOption: W, chBasis: N, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:3, nBasis: 0, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "d0739de688023bba032f4591beaa450e491f5371d7c096f07e1053eabf2ccefe"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/weak_2s"]
[Student "S"]
{One of the characteristics of Weak 2-Bids is that Responder often is unsure how high to go. That's why the 2NT bid is such a great tool. In this case you bid 2NT and partner says 3\H.  

Well, you weren't sure whether to take partner to game or not, so when he says he has a minimum hand you have to pass.}

